<details class="disclosure-item">
<summary>My Story</summary>
<div class="content-block">


<hr class="rule dotted-blue-rule">
  <p>I grew up in rural Maine in the 1980s, splitting my time between long bike rides and my Nintendo. From an early age I knew I wanted to teach. I’ve always enjoyed helping people make sense of complicated ideas and turning difficult problems into something manageable.
</p>

<p>
I studied writing and philosophy as an undergraduate and began my career teaching high school English and history.
</p>

<p>
I earned my master’s in social work in 2012 and worked clinically in community and residential settings, in addition to supervising case managers. I entered private practice ten years ago.
</p>

<p>
Four years ago, I began focusing my work on the psychological development and sociocultural demands facing men — particularly men in critical situations.
</p>

<p>
Outside of work, I still bike and play games, though my tastes have evolved. I have a long-standing interest in personal knowledgebase technology and digital self-determination, including projects built on the AT Protocol and the broader question of users’ rights online.
</p>

<p>
Lately I’ve been playing <em>Assault Android Cactus</em>.</p>
</div>
